{"author":{"id":"138b13306404778af60b1d60d606624fec41556ddac480b2d5f762806ce84fed"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1782958625,"nonce":"Mz8rR0SsL8so0CcFj7ennLQOPto=","kind":"spec","title":"TTY-aware full help (`--full` / `--short`) — Design","content_type":"text/markdown"},{"type":3,"timestamp":1782958625,"nonce":"rvHOyXt9UFwdvUClafNEroYX4hM=","body":"# TTY-aware full help (`--full` / `--short`) — Design\n\n**Date:** 2026-06-30\n**Branch (proposed):** `feat/tty-aware-full-help`\n**Status:** Approved (brainstorming) — pending implementation plan\n\n## Problem\n\nAn agent (or any non-interactive caller) driving `kref` has to probe the CLI\none subcommand at a time to learn its surface, and cobra's stock `--help` shows\nonly a command plus its *direct* children — never the whole tree, the global\nflags' meaning, or the JSON output contract. The cross-cutting facts an agent\nmost needs (that `--json` exists, that errors under `--json` are a\n`{\"error\": \"...\"}` envelope, exit codes) are not discoverable from any single\nhelp screen.\n\nThe original idea was to *detect an LLM caller* and switch output. That signal\ndoes not exist reliably. This design instead keys off an honest, checkable fact\n— **whether stdout is a TTY** — and makes non-interactive help a strict\n*superset* of interactive help.\n\n## Behavior contract\n\n| Invocation | interactive stdout (human terminal) | non-interactive stdout (pipe / redirect / agent) |\n|---|---|---|\n| `kref help` / `kref --help` / `kref -h` / bare `kref` | concise | **full** |\n| `kref help [cmd] --full` | full | full |\n| `kref help [cmd] --short` | concise | concise |\n\n**Detection is per-command-writer, not global `os.Stdout`.** Mode resolves off\n`cmd.OutOrStdout()` type-asserted to `*os.File`: full only when that writer is a\nreal file whose fd is **not** a terminal (a pipe or redirect). Any non-file\nwriter — notably the `*bytes.Buffer` the Ginkgo CLI specs inject via\n`cmd.SetOut` — resolves to **concise**. This keeps tests deterministic\nregardless of how `go test` is run, and means the existing `run(\"--help\")`\nspecs (which assert concise grouping/aliases) keep passing unchanged. The full\npath is exercised in tests via the explicit `--full` flag, never via ambient\nTTY state.\n\n- `--full` and `--short` are **mutually exclusive**. Passing both is an error\n  (`--full and --short cannot be combined`), not a silent precedence rule.\n- **\"Full\"** = the recursive subtree **from the invoked command down**:\n  - root → the whole command tree\n  - a leaf command (most kref commands) → that command's `Long` + all flags +\n    `Example`, with no children section.\n- Non-TTY output is a strict **superset** of TTY output: piping never yields\n  *different* content, only *more*. A human running `kref help | grep X` finds\n  everything they would have seen on screen, plus the rest of the tree.\n\n## Why TTY, not LLM-detection\n\n- There is no reliable signal for \"the caller is an LLM.\" TTY detection\n  (`isatty`) tells you *non-interactive*, which is the honest property to react\n  to. Env-var sniffing (e.g. `CLAUDECODE=1`) only covers hosts hardcoded into\n  the binary and couples kref to moving agent-vendor conventions — rejected.\n- TTY-conditional behavior is idiomatic (`ls` columns/color, `git` pager,\n  `grep --color=auto`). Those switch *presentation*; this switches *content\n  volume*, which is acceptable **only because** non-TTY is a strict superset.\n- Agent ergonomics fall out for free: Claude Code's Bash tool and most agent\n  harnesses capture stdout through a pipe, so `kref --help` lands in non-TTY\n  and yields the full surface with no special flag and no skill to teach an\n  incantation. If a host *does* allocate a pty, the agent degrades gracefully\n  by calling `kref help --full`.\n\n## Architecture\n\n### Entry points (the non-obvious call)\n\nTwo cobra surfaces trigger help, handled differently:\n\n- **The `-h` / `--help` flag path** (and bare `kref`): rendered **TTY-auto\n  only**, via `SetHelpFunc`. No `--full` / `--short` override on this path —\n  cobra's help flag is zero-arg, and an agent never needs the override because\n  non-TTY auto covers it.\n- **A custom `help` command** carries the `--full` / `--short` **local flags**:\n  `kref help [target] [--full|--short]`. Default (no flag) is also TTY-auto.\n  This is the deterministic, testable path — `kref help --full` ignores TTY.\n\nRationale for a custom `help` command instead of persistent root flags:\npersistent `--full` / `--short` would be silently accepted-and-ignored on\n`kref add --full`, a correctness smell. Local flags on the help command cannot\nbe misused that way.\n\n**Constraints the custom help command must preserve:**\n- the `additional` group placement currently set via\n  `root.SetHelpCommandGroupID(\"additional\")` (`cmd/kref/main.go:79`);\n- subcommand-name completion (`kref help \u003cTAB\u003e`), so the recent tree-wide\n  completion work does not regress.\n\n### Rendering (plain text, hand-walked)\n\nA single `renderHelp(cmd, mode)` with `mode ∈ {auto, full, short}`:\n\n- `auto` resolves to `full` / `short` by inspecting `cmd.OutOrStdout()`: full\n  only when it is an `*os.File` whose fd is **not** a terminal\n  (`!term.IsTerminal(int(f.Fd()))`); otherwise concise. This deliberately\n  differs from `output.go`'s `useColor`/`usePager`, which read the global\n  `os.Stdout` — help must key off the command writer so the Ginkgo specs\n  (buffer writer) are deterministic rather than depending on the test\n  process's real stdout.\n- `short` → delegates to **cobra's captured default help func** (grabbed via\n  `root.HelpFunc()` *before* `SetHelpFunc`), preserving the\n  `listAliasesInUsage` usage-template rewrite (`cmd/kref/main.go:99-116`) and\n  the `cli_test` spec that guards it.\n- `full` → custom recursive walk emitting plain text in kref's existing\n  aesthetic: the agent preamble (below), then for each command its\n  name(+aliases) / `Short` / `Long`, flags via cobra's `FlagUsages()`, and\n  `Example`.\n\n`SetHelpFunc` wraps `renderHelp(target, auto)` for the flag/bare path; the\ncustom help command's `RunE` calls `renderHelp(target, modeFromFlags)`.\n\nRejected alternative — `spf13/cobra/doc`: `GenMarkdownTree` writes one file per\ncommand to a directory, not a stdout stream, so single-stream output still\nrequires a manual tree walk; it then emits markdown plus dead `*.md` SEE-ALSO\nlinks that are noise on stdout. The tree walk is unavoidable either way, so\nplain text in the native aesthetic wins.\n\n### Agent preamble (hand-maintained, drift-guarded)\n\nA fixed block prepended to **full** output only, covering what is not inferable\nper-command:\n\n- **Global flags:** `--json`, `--dir`, `--actor`, with their meaning.\n- **Output contract:** human-readable by default; `--json` emits objects;\n  errors under `--json` are `{\"error\": \"...\"}` (see\n  `formatCLIError`, `cmd/kref/main.go:133-140`); exit 1 on failure.\n\n**Drift guard:** a test asserts every global flag named in the preamble exists\non the root command's persistent flags, so renaming/removing a flag fails the\nbuild instead of silently lying to agents.\n\n## Testing\n\nRun via `task test` (wires `KREF_GITLEAKS`); Ginkgo CLI specs:\n\n- `kref help --full` includes a deep-tree command that stock concise help omits\n  (e.g. a `sync` subcommand under `remote`/`bundle`/`vault`).\n- `kref help --short` byte-matches today's concise output.\n- `kref help --full --short` exits non-zero with the mutual-exclusion error.\n- `kref help \u003ccmd\u003e --full` scopes the dump to that command's subtree.\n- Preamble drift guard: each named global flag resolves on `root.PersistentFlags()`.\n- Existing alias-template spec still passes (short path unchanged).\n\n## Out of scope (YAGNI)\n\n- **Companion skill.** The non-TTY auto-default delivers full help to agents for\n  free, removing the skill's reason to exist (and a second source of truth that\n  would drift).\n- **Markdown / man pages / a `kref docs` command.** A docs *site* generator\n  using `cobra/doc` is a separate future effort, not this change.\n- **`--full` / `--short` on the `-h` / `--help` flag path.** Deliberately the\n  `help` command only."}]}